  <header class="consulting-head">
    <h1>Work with me</h1>
  </header>

  <section class="consulting-section consulting-thesis">
    <p>I&rsquo;ve specialized in being a generalist. Some engagements start when a team is trying to figure out a strategy and the situation isn&rsquo;t clear yet. Some start when the program is already running and the team can&rsquo;t tell what is actually happening. Most of my work to date has been in global health and institutional research.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="consulting-section consulting-wounds">
    <ul class="wounds-list">
      <li>A formal process everyone attends and nobody uses to make the decisions it governs. The real decision room is somewhere else, and everyone in the building can tell you where.<span class="wound-aka">AKA <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decoupling" rel="noopener">decoupling</a> (Meyer &amp; Rowan, 1977).</span></li>
      <li>Every actor can explain procedurally why the failure was someone else's piece. The frontline carries the consequence; nobody owns the whole.<span class="wound-aka">AKA the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Problem_of_many_hands" rel="noopener">problem of many hands</a> (Thompson, 1980).</span></li>
      <li>An indicator that improves every quarter while the encounter, outcome, or relationship it was supposed to protect is not. Nobody in the room can say so without sounding like they're against measurement.<span class="wound-aka">AKA <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goodhart%27s_law" rel="noopener">Goodhart&rsquo;s law</a> (1975).</span></li>
      <li>A funded vertical everyone (including the funder) knows shouldn't exist standalone, kept alive because folding it in would force someone to be first to write off the past commitment.<span class="wound-aka">AKA <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Escalation_of_commitment" rel="noopener">escalation of commitment</a> (Staw, 1976).</span></li>
      <li>A leader who has to say something publicly that's defensible, when the technically honest version sounds weaker than what the moment allows.<span class="wound-aka">AKA <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strategic_ambiguity" rel="noopener">strategic ambiguity</a> (Eisenberg, 1984).</span></li>
      <li>A team whose program becomes fragile the moment one person is unavailable, because the work that held it together was never written down.<span class="wound-aka">AKA the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bus_factor" rel="noopener">bus factor</a>.</span></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="consulting-section consulting-getting-started">
    <h2>Getting started</h2>
    <p>If you would like to work together, send me a short or long note about the problem you are working on. I will ask a few follow-up questions to figure out whether I can be useful before either of us puts time or money down. The more context you share, the better I can prepare, and the more useful the first conversation will be. I usually reply within a few days; first calls typically happen within a week or two.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="consulting-section consulting-essay-invitation">
    <p>If you&rsquo;d like to read more before our first call, <a href="/consider-the-tree/">Consider the Tree</a> is the longer written version of how I work.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="consulting-section consulting-working-with-me">
    <h2>Working with me</h2>
    <p>Most engagements start with a paid thought-sparring conversation: <strong>$350 for a 60–90 minute call</strong>. I send a few prep questions a day or two ahead. The call is where I work out whether I can be useful to the situation, and where you work out whether you want to keep going.</p>
    <p>Within a few days after the call, you get a short written follow-up: what I would actually do, what I would want to know more about, and whether I think I am a fit. If we keep going, we agree scope and rate in writing &ndash; usually a fixed-fee deliverable or an hourly block, your preference.</p>
    <p>If $350 is too much, write anyway. Rate flexes for early-stage or public-interest work. I usually have capacity for one or two new engagements at a time.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="consulting-section consulting-deliverables">
    <p>Most engagements take one of these shapes:</p>
    <ul class="deliverables-list">
      <li>Synthesis memos (5&ndash;15 pages) on a question your team can't get clean on, usually after several meetings that haven't converged.</li>
      <li>Program audits. What's working, what's reported as working, where the two diverge. Confidential.</li>
      <li>Problem-framing memos for grant proposals, before the drafting starts. Most proposals that fail in writing failed in framing two weeks earlier.</li>
      <li>Workshop facilitation when the room has been stuck for more than one meeting on the same disagreement.</li>
      <li>Draft text. Policy, IRB, protocol, manuscript framing, board memos. I produce the first draft; you take it from there.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

